
[1]furnace

   FUR'NACE, n. [L. fornax, furnus, either from burning, or the sense is
   an arch.]

   1. A place where a vehement fire and heat may be made and maintained,
   for melting ores or metals, &c. A furnace for casting cannon and other
   large operations is inclosed with walls through which a current of air
   is blown from a large bellows. In smaller operations a vessel is
   constructed with a chamber or cavity, with a door and a grate.

   2. In scripture, a place of cruel bondage and affliction. Deut. 4.

   3. Grievous afflictions by which men are tried. Ezek. 22.

   4. A place of temporal torment. Dan. 3.

   5. Hell; the place of endless torment. Matt. 13.

              FUR'NACE, v.t. To throw out sparks as a furnace.
